metadata.title: Cessna 310
aws::graph::propositions: Accidents and Incidents Involving Cessna 310 Aircraft
On October 28, 1959, a Cessna 310 carrying Cuban revolutionary Camilo Cienfuegos disappeared over the Atlantic Ocean.
The Cessna 310 carrying Camilo Cienfuegos was on a night flight from Camagüey to Havana.
Neither the Cessna 310 aircraft nor the body of Camilo Cienfuegos were ever found.
Camilo Cienfuegos was a Cuban revolutionary.
On November 26, 1962, a private Cessna 310 with aircraft registration PT-BRQ collided in the air with a Saab Scandia 90A-1.
The Cessna 310 PT-BRQ was en route from Rio de Janeiro-Santos Dumont to São Paulo-Campo de Marte.
The Saab Scandia 90A-1 had aircraft registration PP-SRA.
The Saab Scandia 90A-1 PP-SRA belonged to VASP.
The Saab Scandia 90A-1 PP-SRA was on a scheduled domestic service in Brazil from São Paulo-Congonhas to Rio de Janeiro-Santos Dumont.
The collision between the Cessna 310 PT-BRQ and Saab Scandia 90A-1 PP-SRA occurred over Paraibuna, São Paulo.
Both the Cessna 310 PT-BRQ and Saab Scandia 90A-1 PP-SRA were flying on the same airway in opposite directions.
The Cessna 310 PT-BRQ and Saab Scandia 90A-1 PP-SRA failed to have visual contact.
The collision caused both aircraft to crash.
All 23 passengers and crew of the Saab Scandia 90A-1 PP-SRA were killed in the crash.
All four occupants of the Cessna 310 PT-BRQ were killed in the crash.
VASP was an airline operating in Brazil.

text:
## Accidents and incidents
On October 28, 1959, a Cessna 310 carrying Cuban revolutionary Camilo Cienfuegos disappeared over the Atlantic Ocean on a night flight from Camagüey to Havana. Neither the aircraft nor the body of Cienfuegos were ever found.
On November 26, 1962, a Saab Scandia 90A-1, aircraft registration PP-SRA of VASP on a scheduled domestic service in Brazil from São Paulo-Congonhas to Rio de Janeiro-Santos Dumont collided in the air over Paraibuna, São Paulo, with a private Cessna 310 PT-BRQ en route from Rio de Janeiro-Santos Dumont to São Paulo-Campo de Marte. Both were flying on the same airway in opposite directions and failed to have visual contact. The two aircraft crashed killing all 23 passengers and crew of the Saab and the four occupants of the Cessna.
